<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-460-784  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 460 784.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Design  July 17 1989 v28 n14 p4(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>CMOS approach cuts size, cost of intelligent power ICs.andO;(Complementary Metal-oxide Semiconductor, integrated circuits)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Martin, S. Louis.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Power Integrations Inc claims it has developed a new technologythat can break the cost and size barriers currently confrontingintelligent power integrated circuits.andP;  The new technology is apure CMOS process .andP;  The resulting chip interfaces low-voltagecontrol circuitry with high-voltage electromechanical andelectronic devices.andP;  In the new process, p-channel Metal-OxideSemiconductor Field-effect Transistors (MOSFETS) are only 50percent bigger than n-channel MOSFETs.andP;  Power Integration's firstproducts using the new technology are a high-voltage peripheraldriver, an eight n-channel MOSFET array and a universal powerdriver.andP;  All are in the 150- to 275-mA.andP;  range.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Power Integrations Inc. (innovations).andO;Topic:     Cost ReductionPower Semiconductor DevicesIntegrated CircuitsSizeReductionComplementary Metal Oxide SemiconductorsNew TechniqueIntelligent DevicesProduct Development.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>